  "proof_sketch": "Mutation changes initial thread_max from -INFINITY to -1e10f. If all input values are less than -1e10, each thread's max remains -1e10 (since fmaxf(-1e10, val) = -1e10 for val < -1e10). The block reduction then yields global_max = -1e10 instead of the true maximum, causing log-sum-exp to be shifted and output to differ bitwise. For shape [16,16384] float32, values as low as -1e15 are representable; no previous test used such extreme negative values.",
  "survival_reason": "The mutation survived all tests because none of the random seeds or stress policies (including 'all_negative' which uses moderate negative values, or 'mixed_extremes' which uses 1e6 and 1e-6) generated inputs where every element was below -1e10. The kernel's behavior was identical on all tested inputs because the initial -1e10 was always smaller than the actual values, so the max reduction worked correctly. Only when all values are less than -1e10 does the mutation produce a different result. This condition was missed by the test suite.",
  "killable": true,
  "kill_strategy": "Provide an input tensor where all elements are constant -1e15, ensuring that the true maximum is less than -1e10. This will cause the mutated kernel to incorrectly set global_max = -1e10 instead of -1e15, producing a different output from the original.",
  "suggested_test": {
    "description": "All values extremely negative (below -1e10) to trigger mutation in max reduction initialization",
    "python_code": "def generate_inputs(device):\n    import torch\n    return [torch.full((16, 16384), fill_value=-1e15, dtype=torch.float32, device=device)]"
  },
  "recommendations": "Add a test policy for 'extreme_negative' where all values are below -1e10 (e.g., -1e20) to catch mutations that replace -inf with a finite initializer in reduction kernels."
